				<img alt='' src='https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/f0007b920fddf028bb9f392d828f64bb?s=48&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g' srcset='https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/f0007b920fddf028bb9f392d828f64bb?s=96&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g 2x' class='avatar avatar-48 photo' height='48' width='48' loading='lazy'/><span itemprop="name"><a href="http://nimrodflores.com/" class="comment-author-link" rel="external nofollow" itemprop="url">Nimrod Flores</a></span> 			</p>

			<p class="comment-meta"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2014-08-01T02:18:00-07:00" itemprop="datePublished"><a href="https://blog.sucuri.net/2014/07/mailpoet-vulnerability-exploited-in-the-wild-breaking-thousands-of-wordpress-sites.html#comment-3719">August 1, 2014</a></time></p>		</header>

		<div class="comment-content">
			
			<p>If you enabled your regular scans, you should be notified early when you got attacked.</p>
<p>I could be wrong, but I don&#8217;t think Wordfence can really &#8220;prevent&#8221; this kind of attack. In my usage, it only prevents brute force attack and gives me useful warnings and notifications.</p>
		</div>

		
		
